messages.text: Investigation: Day 9
The following is a transcript of the press conference held by the Cedar Creek Sheriff‚Äôs Office regarding the disappearance of Libby Dixon, conducted June 28, 8:02 AM.
Thanks for being here today, folks.
The Cedar Creek Sheriff‚Äôs Office has called this press conference regarding the disappearance of Elizabeth Kay Dixon to fill you in on some recent developments in the case.
The Sheriff‚Äôs Office has searched tirelessly for the missing teen.
Each lead was thoroughly exhausted, and no stone has been left unturned.
Unfortunately, the remains recovered yesterday at Stark‚Äôs Quarry have been positively identified as those of Libby Dixon.
The coroner conducted an autopsy and concluded that her death was a homicide.
His report states that Libby died of blunt force trauma to the skull.
I am heartbroken for Libby‚Äôs family, who ask that you please respect their privacy during this difficult time.
The Sheriff‚Äôs Office welcomes tips from our citizens‚Äî
And the Dixons have offered a $20,000 reward for anyone who comes forward with information about Libby‚Äôs killer.
Someone out there has got to know something about the tragedy that befell this sweet young girl.
Please do the right thing.
Help provide closure for this grieving family.
Help make the streets of Cedar Creek safer.
And help serve justice for the murder of Libby Dixon.
I‚Äôm willing to take a few questions from reporters, but I can‚Äôt discuss confidential information.
My utmost concern is the integrity of this investigation.
So‚Ä¶who‚Äôs got questions for me?
Do you have any suspects, Sheriff?
We‚Äôre looking for information anyone has on the alias ‚ÄúBronco.‚Äù
Is Bronco the prime suspect in Libby‚Äôs murder?
We‚Äôre not ruling anybody out at this point.
Can you verify whether Libby Dixon was pregnant when she was killed?
I decline to comment.
Did Libby seek an abortion prior to her death?
I decline to comment.
Did you find blood in Libby‚Äôs vehicle?
There was no blood in or around her vehicle.
Libby Dixon‚Äôs injuries were strictly internal.
Did Libby die from falling into the quarry, or was she killed somewhere else?
There were drag marks in the gravel from the road to the quarry.
We believe that she passed away before her body was disposed of.
Did you recover forensic evidence at the quarry?
I decline to comment.
Is your son Duke Simmons a suspect, Sheriff?
I decline to comment.
Is your son involved in Libby‚Äôs death?
I decline to comment.
Does he have an alibi?
Okay, folks. That‚Äôs enough.
The Sheriff‚Äôs Office won‚Äôt be taking any more questions at this time.
Thank you for your cooperation in this serious matter. We‚Äôve set up an anonymous tip line at 555-0943.
Please share whatever information you may have that could help us find Libby‚Äôs killer.
I appreciate your time and concern.
The following is a text message conversation between Deputy Decker and Agent Falco, initiated June 28, 1:22 PM.
You out at Stark‚Äôs Quarry, boss?
I‚Äôm still not your boss, Decker.
But yes. Look how clear the water is.
Agent Falco sends Deputy Decker a photograph of a quarry. The site has been flooded with deep, clear groundwater.
This site is abandoned, correct?
Yeah. It hasn‚Äôt been an active quarry for decades now.
I can‚Äôt believe a swimmer found her.
It doesn‚Äôt seem safe to swim out here.
It‚Äôs certainly not.
Technically, the swimmer was trespassing ‚Äî that‚Äôs probably why he remained anonymous.
Could be.
I talked to the coroner this afternoon.
He confirmed Libby‚Äôs pregnancy. She was about six weeks along.
Shit. That poor girl.
So six weeks‚Ä¶
And she disappeared on June 18.
She must‚Äôve conceived sometime around the week of May 5.
Yeah, I think so.
That would‚Äôve been after her depressive episode in March.
So she didn‚Äôt overdose because of a pregnancy.
I reckon not.
She was dating Duke at the time of conception.
She didn‚Äôt break things off with him ‚Äòtil May.
You think it could be his baby?
I don‚Äôt know. But we could test the fetal DNA, assuming the coroner was able to recover any.
We‚Äôd have to get a sample from Duke to compare it to.
Simmons won‚Äôt allow that if we tell him we‚Äôre looking at Duke as a suspect.
Okay, so tell him it‚Äôs an exclusionary sample‚Äî
Get him to think that Bronco is our only suspect.
And we just need to prove Duke‚Äôs not Bronco.
Okay. I‚Äôll talk to Simmons and see if I can get him to cooperate.
Tell me how it goes.
Does Libby‚Äôs family know that the pregnancy‚Äôs been confirmed?
Yeah. Simmons broke the news to them a few minutes ago.
How‚Äôd they take it?
About how you‚Äôd expect, I guess.
Darrence threw a chair across the interview room.
Lynette sobbed uncontrollably.
Anna Mae looked as white as a sheet.
Probably in shock or something.
You find anything at the quarry?
No. The gravel‚Äôs too loose for these footprints to be identifiable.
Take a look.
Agent Falco sends a photograph of vague imprints in loose gravel.
So we‚Äôre shit out of luck.
Don‚Äôt give up on me yet, Tex Decker.
Did the coroner provide an approximate date of death?
Yeah. He said that bodies decompose much faster in freshwater than on land.
Really?
Some scientists think the maggots thrive in the cool water.
Especially in hot weather like we‚Äôve had.
I saw the autopsy photos.
There was some bone exposure.
Yeah. The desiccated tissue helped the coroner narrow down the time of death.
He said it‚Äôs likely she‚Äôd be totally skeletonized had she been in the water more than 9 to 12 days.
So she died approximately 9 to 12 days ago.
According to the coroner, yeah.
Okay.
But if Libby‚Äôs been dead at least 9 days, then who the hell did the clerk see at Wired?
That, boss, is the million-dollar question.
The following is an email exchange between Sidney Pickett and Agent Falco.
The following is an audio call from Director Philomena Todd to Agent Falco, placed June 28, 7:12 PM.
Falco.
Hi, Frankie. It‚Äôs Philomena Todd. I‚Äôve got some news on the Dixon case.
Okay, yeah?
I received the copy of the autopsy report you sent me earlier. I was alarmed to learn of the girl‚Äôs pregnancy.
I had some indications of the possibility, but nothing concrete prior to the autopsy.
We lucked out on the fetal DNA. Any more time in the water and the evidence would‚Äôve been gone.
The coroner sent the sample over to the state lab for testing, and I called them myself to put a rush on the results.
It‚Äôs already been tested?
It can take weeks, if not months, to get the lab to process DNA.
Let‚Äôs just say I called in a favor, okay?
The lab sent the results to me about an hour ago, and there‚Äôs a hit in the system ‚Äî a familial match.
The child is related to an offender in CODIS?
Yes. The offender‚Äôs DNA was collected three years ago. He was arrested for a DUI in Clarksville.
Tennessee only collects DNA in felony DUIs ‚Äî was there a death involved?
No, but he had a minor friend in the car with him who suffered some extensive injuries.
They charged him with ‚Äúchild endangerment with bodily injury.‚Äù
A Class D Felony.
Exactly. He was incarcerated in Memphis from 2014 to 2016 and then moved to Cedar Creek to live with his father, a local mechanic.
The boy‚Äôs name is Jimmy Fitz.
Oh, my god ‚Äî wait.
What is it?
Jimmy Fitz was dating Libby‚Äôs older sister, Anna Mae.
Looks like he was dating Libby, too, huh?
If Jimmy Fitz is related to Libby‚Äôs unborn child, he must be the father.
Indeed.
So this means‚Äî
Jimmy Fitz is ‚ÄúBronco.‚Äù
